ing between Muslims and non-Muslims in the region. Case studies from across these countries of the Malay world take in the rise of the network society in the region in the 1970s up until the early 21st century, providing a panoramic view of Muslim cosmopolitan practices, outlook and visions in the region.Key FeaturesOrganised around 3 key sections: places (covering trade, blogging, sacred spaces); people (covering intellectuals, women); and politics (covering states)Unique in focusing on Muslim cosmopolitanisms in Southeast AsiaShows how local, regional and global factors interact to give rise to cosmopolitan forms of thinkingProvides a counterpoint to a perception of Islam as a divisive force in society  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCosmopolitanismzSoutheast Asia. 0aCultural pluralismxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aIslamzSoutheast Asia. 0aMuslimszSoutheast Asia. 4aIslamic Studies. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311078044440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781474408899zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474408899423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474408899/original  a978-3-11-078044-4  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK